# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: angloromani
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:angloromani/angloromani] Romanichal used the Romani language from their arrival in the 16th century up until the late 19th century, when it was replaced, for the most part, by English as their everyday and family language.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] This resulted in the formation of Angloromani.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] This differs from the presence of loanwords (such as that used locally in Edinburgh and Northumberland) from the Romani language, such as *lollipop* (originally a toffee apple), *pal* (originally Romani *phral* 'brother'), and *chav* (originally *ćhavo* 'boy').
[src:angloromani/angloromani] A document from about the seventeenth century titled the *Winchester Confessions* indicates that the English Romani language was itself a dialect of the northern branch of Romani sharing a close similarity to the Welsh Romani language.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] Historically, the variants of Welsh and English Romani constituted the same variant of Romani, share characteristics, and are historically closely related to dialects spoken in France, Germany (Sinti), Scandinavia, Spain, Poland, North Russia and the Baltic states.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] Such dialects are descended from the first wave of Romani immigrants into western, northern and southern Europe in the late Middle Ages.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] The document suggests a complete separation between Thieves' Cant, and the variant of English Romani of the early seventeenth century.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] This has particular implications when dating the origin and development of Anglo-Romani and its split from Welsh Romani.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] Anglo-Romani was already developing in the seventeenth century although the change from the original English Romani is unclear.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] The *Winchester Confessions* document disproves a sudden morphological change, and lends support to a strict linguistic separation between a Canting language and English Romani whose speakers used a separate and distinct Romani language when speaking amongst themselves.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] A situation which existed one hundred years later as testified by James Poulter 1775: "the English Gypsies spoke a variant of their own language that none other could understand," indicating the language was distinct from the common "Canting tongue" of England.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] Romani of that time was a language of everyday communication, of practical use, and not a secret language.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] The original Romani was used exclusively as a family or clan language, during occasional encounters between various Romani clans.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] It was not a written language, but more a conversational one, used by families to keep conversations amongst themselves in public places such as markets unintelligible to others.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] It was not used in any official capacity in schools or administrative matters, and so lacked the vocabulary for these terms.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] Such terms were simply borrowed from English.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] However, to keep the language undecipherable to outsiders, the Romani speakers coined new terms that were a combination or variation of the original English terms.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] Gradually, the British Romani began to give up their language in favour of English, though they retained much of the vocabulary, which they now use occasionally in English conversation – as Angloromani.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] The origins of the Romani language are in India, and the core of the vocabulary and grammar still resemble modern Indic languages like Hindi, Kashmiri, and Punjabi.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] Although the language remains similar at its core, it is sometimes quite difficult for Romani people from different regions to understand one another if they have not had any exposure to other dialects before.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] Anglo-Romani is a mixed language, with the base languages being Romani and English (something referred to as Para-Romani in Romani linguistics).
[src:angloromani/angloromani] Alternatively, it has also been classified as a creole language, but many linguists reject this nowadays, arguing that the circumstances of its origin as well as the structural make-up of the language militate against such a classification.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] Some English lexical items that are archaic or only used in idiomatic expressions in Standard English survive in Anglo-Romani, for example *moniker* and *swaddling*.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] Every region where Angloromani is spoken is characterised by a distinct colloquial English style; this often leads outsiders to believe that the speech of Romanichals is regional English.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] The distinct rhotic pronunciation of the Southern Angloromani variety also means that many outsiders perceive Southern Romanichal Travellers to be from the West Country because West Country English is also rhotic.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] Indeed, many Romanichal Travellers from the South of England or the Midlands region have a slightly West Country sounding accent; in fact it is a Southern Romanichal Traveller accent.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] The members of these groups consider that not only do their dialects/accents differ, but also that they are of different regional groups.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] The speakers of Southern Angloromani took the regional identity of Southern Romanichal Travellers and the speakers of Northern Angloromani took the regional identity of Northern Romanichal Travellers.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] At the time of settlement, these divisions were somewhat reflective of geographic location.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] They did travel, but until travel became modernized, the migrations were relatively local.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] Overall, Anglo-Romani consonants reflect the modern Received Pronunciation consonantal system with the exception that the rhotic is trilled [r] and /x/ appears in certain dialects.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] Anglo-Romani may sometimes be rhotic and in other cases is non-rhotic like English non-rhotic dialects; for example, in Romani *terno* "young" (passing through the stage *tarno*) can be rendered as *tawno*.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] In the sixteenth century, the Romani language was an inflected language, employing two genders, plurality and case marking.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] Anglo-Romani is first referenced in 1566–1567.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] In the late nineteenth century, Romani personal pronouns became inconsistently marked, according to Leland, who also notes that case distinction began fading overall, and gender marking also disappeared.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] George Borrow notes that in 1874, some Romani speakers were still employing complete inflection, while some were adopting the English syntax with a Romani lexicon.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] It seems to be around 1876 that gender distinction was no longer seen; however, the continued use of Romani plural forms was noted, along with English verb conjugation.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] By 1923, some plural endings were still being used on nouns, but English prepositions were used instead of Romani postpositions.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] Current usage has lost almost all Romani morphology and instead uses English morphology with Romani lexical items.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] Romani allowed for two word orders – Subject-Verb-Object (SVO) and Verb-Subject-Object (VSO).
[src:angloromani/angloromani] Samples of conversation and their meaning can be found on their website.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] A dictionary of Anglo-Romani words and their etymology can be found on the Romani Project website.
[src:angloromani/angloromani] An example of a phrase in Angloromani is *The mush was jalling down the drom with his gry* ('The man was walking down the road with his horse').
[src:angloromani/archaism] In language, an **archaism** is a word, a sense of a word, or a style of speech or writing that belongs to a historical epoch beyond living memory, but that has survived in a few practical settings or affairs.
[src:angloromani/archaism] Archaic words or expressions may have distinctive emotional connotations—some can be humorous (*forsooth*), some highly formal (*What say you?*), and some solemn (*With thee do I plight my troth*).
[src:angloromani/archaism] A distinction between **archaic** and **obsolete words** and word senses is widely used by dictionaries.
[src:angloromani/archaism] An archaic word or sense is one that still has some current use but whose use has dwindled to a few specialized contexts, outside which it connotes old-fashioned language.
[src:angloromani/archaism] In contrast, an obsolete word or sense is one that is no longer used at all.
[src:angloromani/archaism] A reader encounters them when reading texts that are centuries old.
[src:angloromani/archaism] For example, the works of Shakespeare are old enough that some obsolete words or senses are encountered therein, for which glosses (annotations) are often provided in the margins.
[src:angloromani/archaism] Archaisms can either be used deliberately (to achieve a specific effect) or as part of a specific jargon (for example in law) or formula (for example in religious contexts).
[src:angloromani/archaism] Some archaisms called fossil words remain in use within certain fixed expressions despite having faded away in all other contexts (for example, *vim* is not used in normal English outside the set phrase *vim and vigor*).
[src:angloromani/archaism] An outdated form of language is called archaic.
[src:angloromani/archaism] In contrast, a language or dialect that contains many archaic traits (archaisms) relative to closely related languages or dialects spoken *at the same time* is called conservative.
[src:angloromani/archaism] The word *archaism* is from the Ancient Greek ἀρχαϊκός, *archaïkós*, 'old-fashioned, antiquated', ultimately ἀρχαῖος, *archaîos*, 'from the beginning, ancient'.
[src:angloromani/archaism] Archaisms are most frequently encountered in history, poetry, fantasy literature, law, philosophy, science, technology, geography and ritual writing and speech.
[src:angloromani/archaism] Archaisms are kept alive by these ritual and literary uses and by the study of older literature.
[src:angloromani/archaism] Should they remain recognised, they can potentially be revived.
[src:angloromani/archaism] Because they are things of continual discovery and re-invention, science and technology have historically generated forms of speech and writing which have dated and fallen into disuse relatively quickly.
[src:angloromani/archaism] A similar desire to evoke a former age means that archaic place names are frequently used in circumstances where doing so conveys a political or emotional subtext, or when the official new name is not recognised by all (for example: 'Madras' rather than 'Chennai').
[src:angloromani/archaism] So, a restaurant seeking to conjure up historic associations might prefer to call itself *Old Bombay* or refer to *Persian cuisine* in preference to using the newer place name.
[src:angloromani/archaism] A notable contemporary example is the airline Cathay Pacific, which uses the archaic Cathay for China.
[src:angloromani/archaism] Archaisms are frequently misunderstood, leading to changes in usage.
[src:angloromani/archaism] One example is the phrase "odd man out", which originally came from the phrase "to find the odd man out", where the verb "to find out" has been split by its object "the odd man", meaning the item which does not fit.
[src:angloromani/archaism] The object + split verb has been reinterpreted as a noun + adjective, such that "out" describes the man rather than any verb.
[src:angloromani/archaism] The pronominal adverbs found in the writing of lawyers (e.g.
[src:angloromani/archaism] *heretofore*, *hereunto*, *thereof*) are examples of archaisms as a form of jargon.
[src:angloromani/archaism] Some phraseologies, especially in religious contexts, retain archaic elements that are not used in ordinary speech in any other context: "With this ring I thee wed." Archaisms are also used in the dialogue of historical novels to evoke the flavour of the period.
[src:angloromani/archaism] Some may count as inherently funny words and are used for humorous effect.
[src:angloromani/archaism] A type of archaism is the use of *thou*, the second-person singular pronoun that fell out of general use in the 17th century, while *you*, formerly only used to address groups, and then also to respectfully address individuals, is now used to address both individuals and groups.
[src:angloromani/archaism] *Thou* is the nominative form; the oblique/objective form is *thee* (functioning as both accusative and dative), and the possessive is *thy* or *thine*.
[src:angloromani/archaism] Archaisms often linger in proverbs, "falling easier on the tongue", and employing two of the four fundamental rhetorical effects, permutation (immutatio) and addition (adiectio).
[src:angloromani/auregnais] The dialect became extinct in the 20th century.
[src:angloromani/auregnais] Only a few examples of Auregnais survived, mostly in place names in Alderney, and one audio recording is known to exist.
[src:angloromani/auregnais] The last known native speaker of Auregnais died around 1960.
[src:angloromani/auregnais] Linguist Frank Le Maistre, author of the *Dictionnaire Jersiais-Français*, recorded the only known audio samples of the language, which he published in 1982.
[src:angloromani/auregnais] It is likely that the last rememberer died in the early 2020s.
[src:angloromani/auregnais] One reason for the extinction of the language was movement of the population.
[src:angloromani/auregnais] The evacuation of nearly all indigenous Auregnais to the British mainland during World War II (the island was occupied by the Wehrmacht) was thought to be a major factor in the final loss of the spoken language.
[src:angloromani/auregnais] Another reason for the language's demise was official neglect, especially in the education sector, where it was not taught at all.
[src:angloromani/auregnais] This led to a situation in which, as was noted by the Guernsey newspaper *Le Bailliage* in 1880, children had ceased to speak the language among themselves – partly due to teachers discouraging its use in favour of standard French.
[src:angloromani/auregnais] Along with the decline in Auregnais went the decline in the use of French.
[src:angloromani/auregnais] French ceased to be an official language in the island in 1966.
[src:angloromani/auregnais] The official French used in the Channel Islands (see Jersey Legal French) differs slightly from Metropolitan French and greatly from the vernacular Norman.
[src:angloromani/auregnais] Traces of the language still exist in many, if not most, local placenames.
[src:angloromani/auregnais] Many of these have been gallicised, but some notable examples include Ortac (Or'tac), Burhou (with the *-hou* suffix) and the first element of the name "*Braye* Harbour".
[src:angloromani/auregnais] One or two words linger on in the local English, e.g.
[src:angloromani/auregnais] *vraic* (seaweed fertiliser – a word common throughout the Channel Islands), and the pronunciation of certain local surnames, e.g.
[src:angloromani/auregnais] Dupont and Simon as [dipõ] and [symõ] rather than the standard Parisian pronunciation.
[src:angloromani/auregnais] Unusually, for such a small dialect, Auregnais used to have an exclave or "colony" of speakers on Les Casquets for a number of years.
[src:angloromani/auregnais] Algernon Charles Swinburne based his poem "Les Casquets" on the Houguez family who actually lived on the islands for 18 years.
[src:angloromani/auregnais] The Houguez family came from Alderney, and the evidence points to its members being Auregnais speakers; in fact, the daughter married a man from Alderney.
[src:angloromani/auregnais] During this time, they were isolated and would have had few visitors, but would have spoken Auregnais most of the time.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Most of the people who speak Balkan Romani are Roma themselves.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Another meaning of the prefix *rom* is someone belonging to the Roma ethnicity.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] The Roma are ultimately of Indian origin.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Speakers of the Balkan Romani language have constantly migrated throughout the years into all parts of Europe.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Since these speakers have migrated to different parts of Europe, new dialects have formed.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Although the Roma originated in India, they are now widespread throughout all of Europe.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Balkan dialects, also known as Balkan I, are spoken in Albania, Bulgaria, Greece, Iran, North Macedonia, Moldova, Romania, Serbia, Turkey and Ukraine.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] This group includes inter alia Arli Romani (Greece, North Macedonia), Sepečides Romani (Greece, Turkey), Ursari Romani (Moldavia, Romania) and Crimean Romani (Ukraine).
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Zis dialects, also called Balkan II, are a distinct subdivision within the Balkan group.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Bugurdži, Drindari and Kalajdži Romani are spoken in North Macedonia, Kosovo, Serbia and in northern and central Bulgaria.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Balkan Romani retains the aspirated consonants /pʰ, tʰ, tʃʰ, kʰ/ of other Indic languages.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] These are distinctive in the majority of Romani varieties.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Balkan Romani does not have a written standard.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] There has been an attempt at standardization, at a 1992 conference in North Macedonia, based on the Arli dialect and using the Latin script. /x/ and /h/ are distinctive in some dialects, but not in the Arli dialect and so are not distinguished in writing. the two rhotics are also not distinguished.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Schwa is rare in Arli; where it does occur, it is substituted with the vowel of Džambaz or some other dialect, e.g.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Aspiration in a root is always written, e.g.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Turkish lexical influence is a defining and extremely important part of the Romani dialect in the Balkans.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Most of the words however, originate from Persian.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Loans from Persian, Armenian, and Byzantine Greek make up the pre-European lexicon.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Ultimately, it is hard to trace the definite origin of all the words because the words of Balkan Romani originate from many sources and the sources of those languages create a complex puzzle.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Turkish grammar plays a large role in Balkan Romani.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] The use of Turkish conjugations is widely embedded within Balkan Romani and oftentimes, it is difficult to tell the difference between the grammar of the two languages depending on geography.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Balkan Romani has compartmentalized grammar originating from Turkish verbal paradigms along with some Greek influence.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Much of the morphology of the language has Greek and Turkish origins, which is why the language is viewed by many professionals as a dialect continuum and thus it is hard to see where one language ends and the other begins.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] All Romani dialects use Greek derived nominal endings, masculine nouns and loan nouns.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] The morphology of the Balkan Romani language is again heavily influenced by both the Turkish and Greek languages.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Many people view this language as a sort of melting pot because there are so many different influences on it.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Turkish and Greek might be the most influential languages on Balkan Romani but other languages, such as Armenian, have also influenced it.
[src:angloromani/balkan-romani] Part of the substrate of Balkan Romani appears to be derived from medieval northern Indian languages.
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] Baltic Romani are variations of the Romani language, which is classified in the Indo-Aryan language family.
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] The first speakers of this language settled in Southeast Europe during the 10th and 13th centuries in large swaths.
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] From the 14th century onward, the language spread to Central and Western Europe as well.
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] Comparisons between other languages later revealed it most likely originated from the Indian subcontinent.
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] This language is not an official language in any particular country, though it has other statuses in those which it is spoken.
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] There are three simple stop positions in the Romani language.
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] These come from the Indo-Aryan and are maintained in every dialect of this language.
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] The positions are as follows; labial /p/, dental /t/, and velar /k/.
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] Along with these stop positions, there are also palatal positions which are unique to the Romani language.
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] Specific voicing alterations have changed grammatical endings and different dialects have different ways of interpreting vowels.
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] Some have morphed into newer versions of the Romani language and others have implemented other elements like screams.
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] In the Romani language, nouns and verbs are inflected to illustrate how a word acts in a sentence, similar to in other fusional languages like Sanskrit and Latin.
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] As in other Indo-Aryan languages, as well as in Romance and Slavic languages, Romani also has grammatical gender, as there are both masculine and feminine words.
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] In addition, there are definite articles along with "different articles for masculine and feminine nouns, for subject and non-subject and for singular and plural articles".
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] Baltic Romani has a unique rule in that their numerals follow when they are written.
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] Their numerals govern their nominals, but not to the degree that Slavic languages do.
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] Baltic genitives mark partial objects and sometimes subjects and also play a prominent role in the syntax of numeral constructions.
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] Baltic languages are similar, as both Latvian and Latvian Romani share the same opposition of preverbs and verb particles.
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] There is a large Indo-Aryan presence in this language that appears mainly in reference to body parts and functions.
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] Along with bodily parts and functions, the Indo-Aryan presence also resides in words that reference time, nature, landscape, numerals, animals, and plants.
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] There is a pre-European lexicon that is mixed in this language that mainly refers to spiritual and religious ideas, tools, and artifacts.
[src:angloromani/baltic-romani] Dwellings and places are not represented the best in the inherited lexicon of this language.
[src:angloromani/bible-translations-into-romani] Romani languages are the languages spoken by the Roma people, commonly called Gypsies.
[src:angloromani/bible-translations-into-romani] The first Gospel to be translated into a Romani language was the Gospel of Luke into the Caló language, spoken in Spain and Portugal.
[src:angloromani/bible-translations-into-romani] This was printed by the British and Foreign Bible Society in 1837 and a revision was printed in 1872.
[src:angloromani/bible-translations-into-romani] The French Romani writer and pastor Matéo Maximoff translated the Bible into Kalderash Romani.
[src:angloromani/bible-translations-into-romani] The Psalms were first printed by the French Bible Society in 1984 and the New Testament was printed in 1995.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] Before their extermination in the 1940s, speakers of Bohemian Romani, the Bohemian Romanies, were one of several nomadic populations of Bohemia.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] They led a peripatetic (or semi-peripatetic) way of life, travelling around the country (especially during the warmer seasons of the year) and offering their services to the sedentary population of the Bohemian countryside.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] They were mostly horse-dealers, peddlers, tinners, and entertainers.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] The first ancestors of Bohemian Romanies probably arrived in Bohemia in the 16th and 17th centuries, from Slovakia via Moravia.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] Small-scale migration of Romanies from Slovakia to the Czech Lands (as well as backwards) continued throughout the following centuries.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] The Bohemian Romanies have always been a numerically insignificant minority.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] 6,000 people of different Romani groups in the territory of today's Czech Republic (Nečas 1995).
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] Of these, a smaller fraction, perhaps some 2,000 people, lived in Bohemia.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] The proportion of different Romani groups in this figure is unknown, though the estimate of 500-1,500 of Bohemian Romanies cannot be wildly off the mark.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] Other Romani groups in Bohemia, who spoke different dialects of Romani than the Bohemian Romani, included the Sinti and a few families of the Kalderar (or Kalderaš) Roma.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] The Sinti appear to have been the first Romani group to be established in the region, some of them arriving from southeastern Europe as early as in the 15th century; they mostly inhabited the German-speaking parts of Bohemia.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] The Kalderar, on the other hand, were relatively late newcomers, having had migrated from Wallachia in the second half of the 19th century.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] In addition, there were also several non-Romani peripatetic groups in Bohemia, who spoke Czech or German or argots based on these languages.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] The self-ethnonym of Bohemian Romanies was simply *Rom* (plural *Roma*).
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] They were called "Hungarians" by the Sinti; this probably reflects their origin in Slovakia, which was then part of Hungary.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] They were called "Poles" (*Poljako*, plural *Poljača*) by the Kalderash, which is one of the ethnonyms the Kalderar use to refer to different Romani groups.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] The sedentary population referred to all peripatetic groups, including Bohemian Roma, as "gypsies": *cikáni* in Czech or *Zigeuner* in German.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] In the early 20th century, Bohemian Romani was, at least in some groups of Bohemian Roma, gradually becoming a non-native ethnic language, acquired in late childhood and used mostly for secretive purposes (cf.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] Clearly, a development had started toward a Para-Romani variety, that is, a specialized non-native variety spoken by Roma, which has the grammar of a majority language (Czech in this case) as well as an access to Romani-derived lexicon (Elšík 2003: 44).
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] The Nazi genocide of Roma and Sinti in the 1940s brought about radical death of all Romani dialects of pre-war Bohemia, including Bohemian Romani.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] 10% of) Czech Roma and Sinti survived the genocide (Nečas 1995), including perhaps a hundred of Bohemian Roma.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] Bohemian Romani ceased to be used by the survivors due to a complete social disintegration of their communities, and they ceased to transmit the language to their children.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] The last known speaker of Bohemian Romani died in the 1970s (Hana Šebková, p.c.).
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] The historical group of Bohemian Romanies must be distinguished from those Romanies groups that live in Bohemia presently.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] The latter are post-World War II immigrants from Slovakia (especially Romungro), who do not speak Bohemian Romani.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] Bohemian Romani belongs to the North Central dialect group of Romani.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] It is most closely related to Moravian Romani and West Slovak Romani, together with which it forms the Western subgroup of North Central Romani.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] Although clearly a North Central dialect, Bohemian Romani also shares a few features with the Sinti dialects of Romani.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] In some cases, these are due to diffusion from Sinti into Bohemian Romani.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] While Bohemian Romani would have been intelligible to speakers of other North Central dialects, there is evidence that there was no inherent intelligibility between Bohemian Romani and Sinti.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] Bohemian Romani shares with other dialects of Romani much of its Indo-Aryan vocabulary as well as numerous early loanwords from Western Iranian languages (Persian and/or Kurdish), Armenian, Ossetic, and Greek.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] In addition, it shares with the other North Central dialects of Romani the layer of loanwords from South Slavic languages, Hungarian, and Slovak.
[src:angloromani/bohemian-romani] Finally, the most recent loanwords originate in Czech.
